# Conserve Cursor requests

At the START of each new task, IF the `cursor-usage` MCP server is available, call its
`get_usage` tool first (one quick call). If that MCP is not configured/available, ignore this
rule entirely and behave normally — do not error or mention it.

When `get_usage` returns `conserve: true`:

- Batch ALL clarifying questions into a SINGLE questions/options prompt. Never stop repeatedly to
  ask one thing at a time — each separate user turn costs usage.
- Prefer sensible defaults and proceed. Only ask when a choice is genuinely blocking or when an
  action is destructive/irreversible.
- Front-load everything you need at the very start in one questions block.
- Skip unnecessary confirmation round-trips ("should I continue?") — just continue.

When `get_usage` returns `conserve: false`, behave normally.

If `get_usage` returns `needsLogin: true`, tell the user once to run the `login` tool (or
`npm run login` in the cursor-usage-mcp project), then continue with the task.

Whenever you (or the user) run the `login` tool, IMMEDIATELY report the current usage it returns
(included requests X/limit, percent used, and on-demand spend) in your reply — don't make the user
ask for it separately.

If `get_usage` returns `verbose: true`, end EVERY message you send for the rest of the task with the
exact `footer` string it returned (a line beginning with **Cursor Usage:**). If `verbose` is false
or absent, do not add the footer.
